Introduction¶

Brief Overview¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb),including user ratings and revenue. I will perform some wrangling and EDA in order to address some research questions.To get more visual informations , I will use matplotlib to get more insights with visual patterns.

  • Certain columns, like 'cast', 'director' and 'genres', contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.
  • There are some odd characters in the 'cast' column.
  • The final two columns ending with '_adj' show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Questions for Analysis¶

  1. Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  2. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
  3. Do the movies that get high ratings by the audience depend on their length?
  4. Movies runtime is the same over the years?
  5. Top 20 directors in terms of number of movies released?
  6. Type of movies which has the longest duration?

Info for the dataset¶

The dataset contains more than 10,000 movies with 21 variables.
Those Variables are :

  • id
  • imdb_id
  • popularity
  • budget
  • revenue
  • original_title
  • cast
  • homepage
  • director
  • tagline
  • keywords
  • overview
  • runtime
  • genres
  • production_companies
  • release_date
  • vote_count
  • vote_average
  • release_year
  • budget_adj
  • revenue_adj
  • imdb_id : will not use as its not necessary for my analysis.
  • budget_adj and revenue_adj : will not be necessary as they consider only the inflammation overtime in 2010 dollars and I already have budget and revenue so I will neglect both of them.
  • homepage, overview, tagline and keywords columns: they are not playing an important role in our analysis and they have unique values for each row so we can't consider them.

7. Function for splitting cells containing a seperator.¶

In [22]:
#used for splitting any cells containing any separator by giving it the dataframe,column name that need to split,
#separater character and returning the new dataframe

def split_cell(df,column_name,sep):
    df=df.set_index(df.columns.difference([column_name],sort=False).tolist()).apply(lambda x: x.str.split(sep).explode()).reset_index()
    return df

In [29]:
# First getting all the rows which has popularity greater than the mean which is equal to approx 1.
# then grouping by genres and release year 
# counting the number of movies for each genre for each year and saving the counts in a new column
#sorting the counts in descending order to get the max count for each genre for each year at the top
# then removing duplicates to get just the max genre only
df_genre=df_genre.query('popularity >={}'.format(mean_popularity)).groupby(['release_year','genres'])['popularity'].count().reset_index(name="count").sort_values(by=['release_year','count'],ascending=False,axis=0).drop_duplicates(subset='release_year')

Conclusions¶

Results:

  1. Drama and action movies are the most popular over the years.
  2. Comedy genre is getting popular starting from 2000's.
  3. Adventure movie type is the top in the profit chart with profit more than 120 billion dollars.
  4. High profit is indication for high revenue.
  5. Movies runtime is not the main reason for the popularity of the movies.
  6. Runtime is decreasing over the years which attract people to watch the movie without getting bored.
  7. Steven Spielberg is one of the top directors.
  8. History and war movies tend to have long runtime. Limitations:
  • Some of the data are missing so I had to estimate some of them and some to drop.Some didn't affect our analysis as the cast and production companies that I dropped 10% of its rows.
  • The budget and revenue columns contains alot of zero values which I had to drop because it will affect negatively with the analysis, even after dropping them, we didn't get accuarte result beacuse I dropped approximately 60% of the original data.
  • Considering the average count while analyzing is not much accurate cause it differs for each movie dramatically so I used the average vote to minimize that error.
  • Relating to the genres, some movies are considered action while their main nature is adventure so its kind of vague.
  • Some of the directors name are missing but they were small number of rows that this data is missing so I think it will not affect that much in our analysis.
